title: Bump version to 1.1.0 and fixed repo url
Added support for ES2015 generator in repl
Fix 45 - REPL not interactive if a secondary script does not load.
body:
This is intended to address some issues we have when REPL loads scripts.

With this PR:

- The REPL will always instantiate given that `ramdaScript` loads.
- A red indicator will be displayed in the top right corner if `ramdaScript` fails to load. Hovering over it will inform the user of the failure.
- A yellow indicator will be displayed if any other script fails to load. Hovering over it will indicate _which_ script(s) failed. Note that the REPL will be interactive.
- Extra tests relating to script loading have been added.

Relates to: https://github.com/ramda/ramda.github.io/issues/156
Closes: #45

title: Minification and css watch
body:
In this PR
- A minify command (`npm run minify`) is added to reduce JavaScript size. This is presently using the default settings of [uglify-js](https://www.npmjs.com/package/uglify-js). `bundle.js` is reduced from ~2.9M to ~1.6M. (Pre gzip figures) `bundle.css` is already minified in its normal build step. Closes #30?
- The `npm run` commands have been modified to provide additional features:
  - `npm run build-js` will build JS (unminified) with sourcemaps provided thanks to [exorcist](https://www.npmjs.com/package/exorcist) :scream:
  - `npm run watch-js` - as per `build-js` while watching JS files for changes.
  - `npm run build-css` will build CSS.
  - `npm run watch-css` - as per `build-css` but watching for CSS file changes.
  - `npm run watch` combines both `watch-*` commands.
- [README.md](README.md) has been updated to reflect these changes.

title: Some layout / theme tweaks
body:
Hello

Here is a collection of CSS style and layout tweaks, notably:
- the controls are now inline with the titles, saving some vertical space taken up by the titles and controls. The motivation for this is to present a few more lines of code in a more constrained area - potentially desirable should we want to embed this in the docs.
- the colors used in the controls are now based on the same _dracula_ theme we use for the codemirror.
- the controls will no longer go out of sight when scrolling the code
- scrolling one panel will not cause the other to scroll

[Example hosted on github](https://craigdallimore.github.io/ramda.github.io/repl/#?var%20indentN%20%3D%20R.pipe%28R.times%28R.always%28%27%20%27%29%29%2C%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20R.join%28%27%27%29%2C%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20R.replace%28%2F%5E%28%3F%21%24%29%2Fgm%29%29%3B%0A%0Avar%20format%20%3D%20R.converge%28R.call%2C%20%5B%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20R.pipe%28R.prop%28%27indent%27%29%2C%20indentN%29%2C%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20R.prop%28%27value%27%29%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%5D%29%3B%0A%0Aformat%28%7Bindent%3A%202%2C%20value%3A%20%27foo%5Cnbar%5Cnbaz%5Cn%27%7D%29%3B%20%2F%2F%3D%3E%20%27%20%20foo%5Cn%20%20bar%5Cn%20%20baz%5Cn%27)

title: Protocol relative urls
body:
Hello

These tweaks enable the browser to determine whether to use `https` or `http` for the dynamically loaded scripts based on the protocol of the page.

This means they will happily load from a locally running dev server (http) or a github.io [example](https://craigdallimore.github.io/repl/) page. (https).

Additional information: https://www.paulirish.com/2010/the-protocol-relative-url/

title: Introduce tests
body:
Relates to: #7 

Hello

Here is a start for some tests - using [mocha](https://github.com/mochajs/mocha), [sinon](http://sinonjs.org/), [jsdom](https://github.com/tmpvar/jsdom) and [fake-xml-http-request](https://github.com/pretenderjs/FakeXMLHttpRequest) - the latter of which I found more effective than the `sinon` fake XHR / fake server utilities for simulating the shortlink request. Alas even so I had to change `response` to `responseText` in `googl.js` as the library did not simulate that property.

I've made a few changes - hopefully not too heavy handed - in order to make testing a little easier: 
- DOM elements are passed to the various bind-listener-to-element files rather than being looked up in those files. Doing so gives us one place (presently `repl.js`) where we can go to to see which selectors are being used to bind to the DOM, and protects the tests from needing to know the specifics of the DOM.
- A reference to the `console` object is being passed to the `logger` (AKA `reporter`); thus we can spy on wrapped console methods without interfering with the console that the test reporter uses to provide feedback.
- The "clear" and "reset" button behaviours now have their own files so each could be imported and tested individually.

I haven't got to testing the actual code input / output panes themselves. This is already a big collection of changes so I figured it appropriate to share before going further.

![output](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/926283/18614929/b4d5a732-7d90-11e6-85b9-0530cc7cca0d.png)

title: Eslint
body:
Hello!

Delighted that `repl` has its own repo. :tada: 

In the interest of adding some consistency across `ramda` projects, I'm offering/suggesting the style dotfiles from the main `ramda` library be added.

In this PR are the following changes:
- `eslint` and `editorconfig` configuration (adapted for some of the globals)
- `gitignore` and `eslintignore` files (hiding `/node_modules` and `bundle.js` respectively)
- Adjustments to whitespace, quotes, unused varaibles as per the ramda `eslint` config
- Suppression of the `eval` warning
- an `npm run lint` command that will lint the files in `./lib`.

I wasn't sure what to do about the files in `/example` so they are not linted at present. #1 

Totally happy to drop this or make adjustments if this is controversial.

title: Pre-integration CSS tweaks
body:
Hello

I've been experimenting with this REPL on the "Try Ramda" page and noticed it needed a few CSS changes to avoid taking on some unwanted styles declared by the presence of bootstrap on that page.

In this PR:
- The heading size is made more explicit
- The console and error elements will not have bootstrap-style white backgrounds
- The console and error elements will not push down the output code when they have no content
- The dividing line will take the full height of its container, even when the container is greater than the height of the page.

title: Graceful script loading
body:
Hello

Here is an attempt at adding a bit more feedback / control over script loading. It's a bit cursory, I hope it might lead to things like enabling dynamically loaded external resources (dropdown with ramda versions, perhaps?). For now it might help with handling errors when loading external scripts.

At present this will enable us to define (with a bit of JSON) which scripts we would like to load and how they will be exposed on the `window` object. Upon instantiation, _repl_ will load the scripts - first `ramda`, then - given that succeeds - the rest of the scripts in parallel.

While they load a spinner is presented, and upon a successful load the repl controls become enabled. If a script _fails_ to load the repl will not start, and a very basic error message is displayed. One way to test this is to give an incorrect `src` within the config.

Of note: The repl will have `ramda` and `ramda-fantasy` baked in as part of its implementation. This is intended to trade a bit of extra downloading for the ability to load any version of ramda (and friends) without needing to be concerned how API movement might impact the repl code.
### Spinner

![spin](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/926283/19250949/d28cbfd0-8f34-11e6-9290-daafc4f2260c.png)
